&lt;p>Aims:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Provide advanced research training and development activities related to multilingualism.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Encourage application of well-established research methods from sociolinguistic studies of multilingualism to other social science disciplines, particularly education.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Develop dedicated research training materials and facilitate international dialogue among researchers running research methodology courses for postgraduate students researching in multilingual contexts.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Events include: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>A five-day residential course: Researching multilingualism: key concepts, methods and issues (University of Birmingham, July 2010 and April 2011).&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Follow-up support days.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>A workshop: Transcribing bilingual discourse at the ESRC Centre for Research on Bilingualism (Bangor University).&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>One-day regional workshops on specific themes (at the Universities of Birkbeck, Cardiff, Goldsmiths, Leeds, Strathclyde). &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>2 master-classes.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Ongoing development of specialist research training materials.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>A final conference.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>For sustainability, project activities are embedded within the UK Linguistic Ethnography Forum (special interest group, British Association for Applied Linguistics).&lt;/p>

